The film Argo: when everything is worse, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrators made up of Islamist students took over the US embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They should be released in exchange for the Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who supported his regime for decades.
The situation didn't offer to the US administration of positive outcome, she couldn't abandon the Shah, because it has seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was able to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, blow compounded later by the fiasco of the attempt to rescue hostages by force.
Diplomats kidnapped were eventually released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States prompted a wave of solidarity and a sense anti-Iran government from emerging.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in the face of Ronald Reagan in the presidential elections of 1980.
The film Argo, the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, escaped six employees of the embassy.
After a few detours complicated, they met in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through an implausible coverage: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a crew doing the repérages for shooting a film epic of fiction.
Combination of genres
The plan of the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requit collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magasines did rule of this film project, press conferences were held and a production company was fictitious real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
The film, Affleck is an unusual combination of different genres.
It is a part of a political thriller designed realistic but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, a betrayal - as, for example, in the trilogy "Ocean's seen, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres are unfolding: footage of Tehran to documentary style (in the sequences are presented iconiques captioned photographs of the days of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been retranscrites in the film, there is no great difference)
Lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
And then scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other agencies with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career so remarkable.
Actor ridiculed, he became a respected director and his acting has ceased to be ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also the first movie to Affleck who is not taking place in his home city of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that would put his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also is showing that sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is required" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film takes place in the streets during the reconstruction of actual facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity that also suggests the confusion and unpredictability arising when suddenly, in a given location, wrote a page of history.
Affleck and his staff get a similar effect in the fictitious scenes (the wrong camera crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many shares at too many places
The director had to settle for a subject which was in fact little thrilling scenes, the film sense of the term.
He fared well, he sometimes add some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a telephone call in America and the continued on the runway are quite far-fetched).
The weakness of Argo lies in his character dissipated, due to the need to show too many things to too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are delightful in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters have deserved greater attention and they are far from alone.
The film of Affleck lack a bit of tension, he allows himself to do with moderate interest, appreciating the achievement and the retro style of the 1970s.
It leads to the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story yet somehow incomplete to date, and as illustration of the character exaggeration of the representation of the secret services as omnipotents and omniscient, he made the case.

