The summit of the Unasur ended without the Declaration of Lima is made public
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended in Peru today without the Declaration of Lima has been made public, although it has been previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 proxies present.
EFE has tried repeatedly to access the document signed during the sixth Oedipus Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but the Department of Foreign Affairs and the presidency reported initially that he would be released after the close of the summit, then said that it would be published at a moment's notice on the website of the Peruvian government.
When they were interviewed on the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists "access to information about the summit has consistently been limited.
During the day, only the video without the presidential meeting with the message, "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating among the journalists were those of the officers of some of the governments of the Unasur attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document disclosed during the day was the list of presidents here, which has caused unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media demanding information more important.
Later, the presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not the official document that has reached the summit.
In October, Peru has been the host of the 3rd summit of South American and Arab countries (takes) and, on this occasion, although this has been insisted by the press, he had not released the statement also called the Declaration of Lima, as had been previously announced.
On the official website of the takes, we can verify that the document was published in March.
In the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to put in place systems safe for all journalists, but they have the most limited obtaining information.
The summit has also signed a joint agreement with Chile and Peru to accept the judgment of the Court in The Hague, which settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the decision of the ICJ to hear the pleas of both parties in the lawsuit that Lima filed against Santiago and that begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect the verdict and exécuterons who solve disputes that we wear today in this international court", said President Humala, beside his Chilean counterpart.
"The Chile has always been, and will continue to be a country that respects international law to the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals", added President Piñera giving a handshake to President Humala, beside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of two presidents that they submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia has denounced this week the Stability Bogota by which it had agreed to abide by the decisions of the international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua she considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from the Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala has been asked to open the deliberations in the morning and close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The trustee has read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of $17 million investment.
