With Europe in crisis, "the economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not have a matrix triomphaliste but should help increase our matrix productive and to see a better future for our people", concluded the President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection spaces for South America, particularly in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and generating new economic system", said the Peruvian president in a speech.
Among these projects, he noted that five were Peru and were on the broad lines of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two targeted a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give any more details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation of Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America remains a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another topic at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian president, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to discuss calmly of maritime dispute through the ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
